{{Infobox language family |name=Border |altname=Tami River – Bewani Range |region=[[New Guinea]] |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[North Papuan languages|North Papuan]]? |child1=Taikat |child3=''Senggi'' |child2=Bewani |child4=''Morwap'' |glotto=bord1247 |glottorefname=Border }}
The '''Border''' or '''Upper Tami'''<ref>Cowan (1957) tentatively proposed a "Tami" family, named after the [[Tami River]], that included the modern Border and [[Sko languages|Sko]] language families. Some of the previously unclassified languages did turn out to be Sko, and were added to that family; the remainder (including the languages of the upper Tami) constitute the Border family.</ref> languages are an independent [[language family|family]] of [[Papuan languages]] in [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]]'s version of the [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] proposal. They are named after the Indonesia – Papua New Guinea border, which they span.
==Classification==
* ''[[Morwap language|Morwap]]'' (Elseng) * ''[[Senggi language|Senggi]]'' (Viid) * '''Taikat''' (Upper Tami): [[Awyi language|Awyi]], [[Taikat language|Taikat]] * '''Bewani Range''' **''[[Manem language|Manem]]'' **Poal River: [[Ainbai language|Ainbai]], [[Pagi language|Pagi]], [[Kilmeri language|Kilmeri]] (Mbo) **Bapi River: [[Amanab language|Amanab]], [[Auwe-Daonda language|Auwe-Daonda]], [[Imonda language|Imonda]], [[Sowanda language|Sowanda]] (Punda, Umeda, Waina), [[Waris language|Waris]]
There is also [[Ningera language|Ningera]].
Laycock classified Morwap as an isolate, but noted pronominal similarities with Border. Ross included Morwap in Border but noted that they do not appear to share any lexical similarities. However, his Morwap data were quite poor. Usher included it as a branch of Border.
