# [[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som6.html ''Transmontano'']—[[Trás-os-Montes e Alto Douro]].

=== Other countries and dependencies ===
* {{flag|Angola}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://www.cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som85.html ''Angolano''] ([[Angolan Portuguese]])
* {{flag|Cape Verde}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som87.html ''Cabo-verdiano''] ([[Cape Verdean Portuguese]])
* {{flag|East Timor}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som84.html ''Timorense''] ([[East Timorese Portuguese]])
* {{flag|India}} — ''Damaense'' ([[Damanese Portuguese]]) and ''Goês'' ([[Goan Portuguese]])
* {{flag|Guinea-Bissau}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som88.html ''Guineense''] ([[Guinean Portuguese]])
* {{flag|Macau}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som92.html ''Macaense''] ([[Macanese Portuguese]])
* {{flag|Mozambique}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som89.html ''Moçambicano''] ([[Mozambican Portuguese]])
* {{flag|São Tomé and Príncipe}}—[[File:Loudspeaker.svg|11px]] [http://cvc.instituto-camoes.pt/hlp/geografia/som83.html ''Santomense''] ([[São Tomean Portuguese]])
* {{flag|Spain}}—[[Alentejan Portuguese|Oliventian Portuguese]] and other varieties sometimes controversially deemed as separate languages, such as [[Galician language|Galician]] and ''[[Fala language|Fala]]''.
* {{flag|Uruguay}}—[[Riverense Portuñol language|''Dialectos Portugueses del Uruguay (DPU)'']]

Differences between dialects are mostly of [[Accent (dialect)|accent]] and [[vocabulary]], but between the Brazilian dialects and other dialects, especially in their most colloquial forms, there can also be some grammatical differences. The [[Portuguese creole|Portuguese-based creoles]] spoken in various parts of Africa, Asia, and the Americas are independent languages.

=== Characterization and peculiarities ===
[[File:Portugués_europeo.png|thumb|left|200px|Map highlighting the different [[Accent (sociolinguistics)|accents]] within the Portuguese Republic]]
Portuguese, like [[Catalan language|Catalan]], preserved the stressed vowels of [[Vulgar Latin]], which became diphthongs in most other Romance languages; cf. Port., Cat., Sard. ''[[wikt:pedra|pedra]]'' ; Fr. ''{{wiktfr|pierre}}'', Sp. ''{{wiktes|piedra}}'', It. ''{{wiktit|pietra}}'', Ro. ''{{wiktro|piatră}}'', from Lat. ''{{wiktla|petra}}'' ("stone"); or Port. ''{{wiktpt|fogo}}'', Cat. ''{{wiktca|foc}}'', Sard. ''{{wiktsc|fogu}}''; Sp. ''{{wiktes|fuego}}'', It. ''{{wiktit|fuoco}}'', Fr. ''{{wiktfr|feu}}'', Ro. ''{{wiktro|foc}}'', from Lat. ''{{wiktla|focus}}'' ("fire"). Another characteristic of early Portuguese was the loss of [[:wiktionary:intervocalic|intervocalic]] ''l'' and ''n'', sometimes followed by the merger of the two surrounding vowels, or by the insertion of an [[epenthesis|epenthetic vowel]] between them: cf. Lat. ''{{wiktla|salire}}'' ("to jump"), ''{{wiktla|tenere}}'' ("to hold"), ''{{wiktla|catena}}'' ("chain"), Sp. ''{{wiktes|salir}}'', ''{{wiktes|tener}}'', ''{{wiktes|cadena}}'', Port. ''{{wiktpt|sair}}'', ''{{wiktpt|ter}}'', ''{{wiktpt|cadeia}}''. 

When the [[elision|elided]] consonant was ''n'', it often [[nasalization|nasalized]] the preceding vowel: cf. Lat. ''{{wiktla|manum}}'' ("hand"), ''{{wiktla|ranam}}'' ("frog"), ''{{wiktla|bonum}}'' ("good"), Port. ''{{wiktpt|mão}}'', ''{{wiktpt|rãa}}'', ''{{wiktpt|bõo}}'' (now ''{{wiktpt|mão}}'', ''{{wiktpt|rã}}'', ''{{wiktpt|bom}}''). This process was the source of most of the language's distinctive nasal diphthongs. In particular, the Latin endings ''{{wiktla|-anem}}'', ''{{wiktla|-anum}}'' and ''{{wiktla|-onem}}'' became ''{{wiktpt|-ão}}'' in most cases, cf. Lat. ''{{wiktla|canis}}'' ("dog"), ''{{wiktla|germanus}}'' ("brother"), ''{{wiktla|ratio}}'' ("reason") with Modern Port. ''{{wiktpt|cão}}'', ''{{wiktpt|irmão}}'', ''{{wiktpt|razão}}'', and their plurals ''-anes'', ''-anos'', ''-ones'' normally became ''-ães'', ''-ãos'', ''-ões'', cf. ''cães'', ''irmãos'', ''razões''. 

The Portuguese language is the only [[Romance language]] that has preserved the clitic case [[mesoclisis]]: cf. ''{{lang|pt|dar-te-ei}}'' (I'll give thee), ''{{lang|pt|amar-te-ei}}'' (I'll love you), ''{{lang|pt|contactá-los-ei}}'' (I'll contact them). Like [[Galician language|Galician]], it also retains the Latin synthetic [[pluperfect]] tense: ''{{lang|pt|eu estivera}}'' (I had been), ''{{lang|pt|eu vivera}}'' (I had lived), ''{{lang|pt|vós vivêreis}}'' (you had lived).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GILmCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=latin+synthetic+pluperfect+also+in+portuguese%23#v=onepage&q=latin%20synthetic%20pluperfect%20also%20in%20portuguese%23&f=false|title=Tense and Aspect: From Semantics to Morphosyntax|isbn=9780195091939|last1=Giorgi|first1=Alessandra|last2=Pianesi|first2=Fabio|year=1997}}</ref> [[Romanian language|Romanian]] also has this tense, but uses the -s- form.

