{{Main article|Portuguese orthography}}
Portuguese is written with 26 letters of the [[Latin script]], making use of five [[diacritic]]s to denote stress, vowel height, contraction, nasalization, and etymological [[assibilation]] ([[acute accent]], [[circumflex]], [[grave accent]], [[tilde]], and [[cedilla]]). The [[Diaeresis (diacritic)|trema]] was also formerly used in Brazilian Portuguese, and can still be encountered in words derived from proper names in other languages, such as Anhangüera and mülleriano.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brazil-help.com/recent_changes.htm|title=Most Recent Changes to the Portuguese Language}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moderna.com.br/acordo/guia_acordo.pdf|deadurl=yes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601092927/http://www.moderna.com.br/acordo/guia_acordo.pdf|archive-date=1 June 2010|title=Guia do Acordo Ortográfico|publisher=Moderna|language=pt}}</ref> Accented characters and [[digraph (orthography)|digraphs]] are not counted as separate letters for [[collation]] purposes.

