{{About|the Scouts|other meanings|Three-finger salute (disambiguation)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}} [[File:Plast - Scout Salute.jpg|thumb|Ukrainian Girl Scout from [[Plast]] making the Scout Sign.]] The '''three-finger salute''' is used by members of [[Scouting|Scout and Guide]] organizations around the world when greeting other Scouts and in respect of a national flag at ceremonies. In most situations, the salute is made with the right hand, palm face out, the thumb holding down the little finger, and with the fingertips on the brow of the head. There are some variations of the salute between national Scouting organizations and also within some programme sections.
A "half-salute", known as the Scout Sign, is also used in certain situations. The hand is still held palm facing out, and the thumb holding the little finger, but the hand is held at the shoulder instead. Other organizations with historical ties to Scouting such as [[Scouts Royale Brotherhood]] and [[Alpha Phi Omega]] use it as well.
== Meaning of the three fingers == [[Image:1996-Rover Moot-Fahnengruß.jpg|thumb|200px|Scouts using the three-finger salute as the Scout Sign.]] [[Image:Lebkuchen in Form des Pfadfindergrußes 3755.jpg|thumb|A Christmas cookie as three-finger salute.]] In his book, ''Scouting for Boys'', [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Baden-Powell]] chose the three-finger salute for Scouts to represent the three aspects of the [[Scout Promise]]: # Honor God and Country # Help Others # Obey the [[Scout Law]]<ref name="SfB_2005">{{cite book |first=Robert |last=Baden-Powell |authorlink=Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell |title=[[Scouting for Boys]] |year=2005 |orig-year=First published 1908 |publisher=Oxford |page=37}}</ref>
=== Cub Scouts' two-finger salute === [[Cub Scout]] sections can use a [[two-finger salute]], depending on the national Scouting organization they belong to. This is done to represent the two rules of the original Cub Scout / Wolf Cub law. In [[The Wolf Cub's Handbook]], Baden-Powell wrote: ''Why two fingers? Well, you know what a Wolf's head looks like with two ears cocked up. It is used as the badge of the Wolf Cub. Your two fingers in the salute are the two ears of the Wolf."''<ref>[http://www.thedump.scoutscan.com/wolfcubshandbook.pdf The Wolf Cub's Handbook] (p.15)</ref> The salute is performed with the right hand.
== Salute or sign? == Originally, Baden-Powell intended for Scouts to salute each other in greeting when they first saw each other for the first time using the "secret sign", or half-salute. This was regardless of whether the Scouts knew each other or not. Officers, such as Patrol Leaders, Scoutmasters, or members of the armed forces, were to be saluted with a full-salute.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article88440459 Prahran Chronicle (Vic. : 1914 - 1918)(Saturday 17 July 1915, page 5]</ref><ref>[http://www.inquiry.net/traditional/por/general_rules.htm P.O.R. iX. General Rules, Rule 352]</ref>
Full-salutes were also required at the hoisting of the [[Union Flag]], the playing of the national anthem, or at funerals.<ref name="SfB_2005"/>
== Canada == In [[Scouts Canada]] the Salute is rendered vertically, palm out similar to British Army/Commonwealth salutes, except if the member is a Sea Scout where it is palm in/angled down. (Traditionally, to hide your 'dirty hands' from the ship's captain). [[Beavers (Scouting)|Beaver Scouts]] in Canada use a variant of the two-fingered sign with the fingers bent forwards forming "teeth". When they move up to [[Cub Scout]]s part of the ceremony sometimes includes a Scouter straightening the fingers to change from the Beaver to Cub sign.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}
== Switzerland == The half-salute is used by Swiss Scouts when shaking (left) hands with other Scouts or leaders on greeting or parting.
Additional meaning of the thumb holding down the little finger as explained in Switzerland: the big and strong protects the weak and little.
== United Kingdom == [[The Scout Association]] uses the three-fingered salute for all sections, including Cub Scouts. The two-fingered Cub salute was abandoned by the Scout Association following a recommendation by the [[The Chief Scouts' Advance Party Report|Advance Party Report]] in 1966, that ''"there should be only one salute for the whole Movement"''.<ref>[http://www.thedump.scoutscan.com/advance66.pdf The Advance Party Report '66] (Recommendation 10, p.14)</ref> The Scout Sign is used while making or reaffirming the Beaver Scout, Cub Scout or [[Scout Promise]] and at no other time.<ref>[http://scouts.org.uk/documents/por/2011updates/Chap_12_2011.pdf The Scout Association - Policy, Organisation and Rules - January 2011: Rules 12.5 and 12.6]</ref> The [[Baden-Powell Scouts' Association]] uses both the three and two fingered salutes. [[Girlguiding UK]] only uses the Guide Sign (half salute).<ref>[http://www.girlguiding.org.uk/about_us/international_guiding/wagggs.aspx GirlguidingUK: World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts (WAGGGS) - Symbols of Unity]</ref>
== United States of America == [[File:Texas Cub Scouts Saluting.jpg|thumb|Texas Cub Scouts Saluting]]
=== Baden-Powell Service Association === As a member of [[World Federation of Independent Scouts|WFIS]] and part of the international [[Traditional Scouting]] movement. the scout sign and salute differs by section in the [[Baden-Powell Service Association|BPSA-US]]. The Timberwolf (cub) section uses the two-finger (spread) salute, and the two finger scout salute as defined in the 1938 PO&R,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inquiry.net/traditional/por/general_rules.htm|title=IX. General Rules|website=www.inquiry.net|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref> while the Pathfinder (scout) and Rovers use the traditional three-finger sign and salute.
=== Boy Scouts of America === Cub Scouts use the two finger Scout sign and salute— the sign is presented with the fingers apart to represent the ears of [[Akela (Scouting)|Akela]] the wolf. Boy Scouts{{Update after|2019|02|01|reason=Scouts BSA}}, Varsity Scouts, Venturers and Sea Scouts use the three finger sign and salute. The Scout Sign is performed with the upper arm parallel to the ground and the forearm vertical, forming a right angle at the elbow.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://blog.scoutingmagazine.org/2012/10/17/bsa-to-use-scout-oath-and-scout-law-for-all-programs/ |last=Wendell |first=Bryan |title=BSA to use Scout Oath and Scout Law for all programs |work=Scouting |department=Bryan on Scouting |date=17 October 2012}}</ref> The Scout Sign is used when reciting any of the ideals of the BSA such as the Scout Oath and Scout Law. It is also used to gain the attention of the group.
The salute is rendered in the American style with the palm in and is only used to salute the [[flag of the United States]]. Early BSA protocol required Scouts to salute each other, but this was discontinued in 1972.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}
=== Girl Scouts of the USA === As a member of [[WAGGGS]], the [[Girl Scouts of the USA]] use the three-fingered sign at shoulder height. The three fingers represent the person's own spiritual beliefs, other people and the Girl Scout Law. This differs from the 1913 version where the first finger represented God and Country.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cadette Girl Scout Handbook |publisher =[[Girl Scouts of the USA]] |year=1995 |isbn=0-88441-283-0}}</ref>
== Worldwide == All [[World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts]] members share the three fingered sign, with the palm facing out held at shoulder height, elbow by the side and the thumb holding the little finger. This is used in numerous situations of respect including when making or reciting the [[Scout Promise|Promise]], receiving awards, honouring a flag, honouring the dead and meeting other Girl Guides and Girl Scouts. In the latter case, it may be used in conjunction with the [[Scout handshake|left handshake]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}
